    </section>
  </main>

    <p>Built by Your Name — © <span id="year"></span></p>
  </footer>

  <script>
    // show current year
    document.getElementById('year').textContent = new Date().getFullYear();
  </script>
</body>
</html>

style.css (optional — save as portfolio/style.css)

2) Initialize repo and push the base page to main

Open a terminal in the portfolio folder and run these commands (edit the remote URL for your GitHub username):

bash
# one-time: create project folder and files (if you haven't already)
mkdir portfolio && cd portfolio
# create files as above, and put your photo at images/me.jpg
mkdir images
# (copy your me.jpg into images/)

# initialize git
git init

# stage files
git add .

# initial commit
git commit -m "Initial portfolio page"

# Create the remote repo on GitHub first (use the website).
# Then set main branch as default locally and push:
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/<your-username>/portfolio.git
git push -u origin main

Notes

  • Replace <your-username> with your GitHub username.

  • If your GitHub repo is private and your teacher needs access, add them as a collaborator (or make it public).

3) Create a development branch and make changes there

Make a development branch, add the profile picture/styling (or any changes), commit, and push:

bash
# create and switch to development branch
git checkout -b development

# (make changes — e.g., add style.css, update HTML, add image)
git add .
git commit -m "Add profile picture and styling"

# push development branch to GitHub
git push -u origin development

Commit message tips:

  • Keep them short + descriptive:

    • Initial portfolio page

    • Add profile picture and styling

    • Update bio and contact info

    • Fix image path

4) Merge development → main

You can merge locally via command line or using a Pull Request on GitHub. Both ways shown:

Option A — Command line merge

bash
# make sure main is up-to-date
git checkout main
git pull origin main

# merge development into main
git merge development

# if merge created a commit locally:
git push origin main

If there are conflicts, Git will show files with conflicts. Resolve conflicts in your editor (look for <<<<<<< markers), then:

bash
git add <fixed-file>
git commit -m "Resolve merge conflicts: <file>"
git push origin main

Option B — GitHub Pull Request (recommended for classroom workflow)

  1. On GitHub open your repo → "Pull requests" → "New pull request".

  2. Set base: main, compare: development.

  3. Create the PR, review changes, then click Merge pull request → Confirm merge.

  4. Pull the merged main locally:

bash
git checkout main
git pull origin main

5) Verify everything (quick checklist you should follow)

  • Repo URL shared (public or teacher added as collaborator).

  • index.html loads in the browser (open index.html locally or view GitHub Pages if deployed).

  • Your picture displays (image path images/me.jpg).

  • You pushed changes to main, then created/used development, pushed to development, then merged back into main.

  • Commit messages are clear and explain intent (examples above).

6) Extra helpful commands & troubleshooting

Show branches:

bash
git branch --all

Check status:

bash
git status

View commits:

bash
git log --oneline --graph --decorate

If you accidentally committed to main and want to continue with development-first workflow:

bash
# create development from main's current state
git checkout -b development
git push -u origin development
# now continue work on development and merge later as shown above

7) (Optional) GitHub Pages — view your page online

If you want to publish the page, enable GitHub Pages in the repo settings and choose the main branch (or gh-pages if you create that). After enabling, GitHub gives you a URL where index.html will load.

  1. Open Visual Studio Code.

  2. Click File → Open Folder…

  3. Choose or create a folder named portfolio (for example on your Desktop) and open it.

    • So your path might be:
      C:\Users\<you>\Desktop\portfolio

📁 Step 2 — Create your project files

Inside VS Code:

  1. In the Explorer panel (left sidebar), click New Folder and name it:

    nginx
    images

  2. Inside the portfolio folder, click New File and name it:

    diff
    index.html

  3. (Optional) Also create a New File for styling:

    style.css

Your folder structure should look like this inside VS Code:

pgsql
portfolio/
├─ index.html
├─ style.css
└─ images/

Then place your picture inside the images/ folder and name it:

vbnet
me.jpg

💻 Step 3 — Write your HTML code

  1. Open the index.html file in VS Code.

  2. Paste this code exactly (you can edit your name, bio, and email later):

html
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <title>Your Name — Portfolio</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <header class="hero">
    <img src="images/me.jpg" alt="Photo of Your Name" class="profile-photo">
    <h1>Your Name</h1>
    <p class="bio">
      Hi! I’m a beginner web developer learning HTML, CSS, and Git. 
      I enjoy building small projects and exploring creative ideas.
    </p>
  </header>

  <main>
    <section>
      <h2>Contact</h2>
      <p>Email: <a href="mailto:you@example.com">you@example.com</a></p>
    </section>
  </main>

  <footer>
    <p>Built by Your Name — © <span id="year"></span></p>
  </footer>

  <script>
    document.getElementById('year').textContent = new Date().getFullYear();
  </script>
</body>
</html>

  1. Press Ctrl + S (or Cmd + S on Mac) to save.

3) Initialize Git and push the base page to main on GitHub

A few notes: you must first create an empty repository named portfolio on GitHub (via the website). After creating it, you will have a remote URL like https://github.com/<your-username>/portfolio.git.

Now run:

bash
# initialize repo
git init

# stage files
git add .

# initial commit
git commit -m "Initial portfolio page"

# set main branch name
git branch -M main

# add your GitHub repo as remote (replace <your-username>)
git remote add origin https://github.com/<your-username>/portfolio.git

# push to GitHub (first push sets upstream)
git push -u origin main

Authentication: Git Bash will ask for your GitHub credentials. If you use HTTPS, GitHub now requires a personal access token (PAT) instead of your password. If you prefer, set up SSH and use the SSH remote (e.g., git@github.com:<your-username>/portfolio.git) — that avoids typing PAT each time.

4) Create and work on development branch, commit changes

Switch to a development branch, make changes (for example add or tweak styling or update the bio), commit and push:

bash
# create and switch to development
git checkout -b development

# (make changes now in VS Code, e.g., edit index.html or style.css)
# after editing, stage and commit:
git add .
git commit -m "Add profile picture and styling"

# push development branch to remote
git push -u origin development

Suggested commit messages:

  • Initial portfolio page

  • Add profile picture and styling

  • Update bio and contact info

  • Fix image path

5) Merge development → main from the command line

Option A — fast merge if no conflicts:

bash
# ensure main is up-to-date
git checkout main
git pull origin main

# merge development into main
git merge development

# push merged main to GitHub
git push origin main

Option B — if you want to follow a Pull Request workflow, create a PR on GitHub UI, merge there, then:

bash
# update local main after merging on GitHub
git checkout main
git pull origin main

6) If you get merge conflicts

Git will show conflicted files. Resolve conflicts in those files (open them in VS Code, look for <<<<<<<, =======, >>>>>>>), then:

bash
# after resolving conflicts in files:
git add <file1> <file2>
git commit -m "Resolve merge conflicts: <file-names>"
git push origin main

7) Helpful commands to verify status & history

bash

git status

# view commit history graph
git log --oneline --graph --decorate

# show branches
git branch -a

# fetch remote changes without merging
git fetch origin

html
<span id="year"></span>

  • new Date() → Creates a JavaScript date object representing the current date and time.

  • .getFullYear() → Gets the current year from that date (like 2025).

  • .textContent = ... → Puts that year inside the <span> element.

Ah! You’re asking about the <meta> tags in your HTML. Let me explain clearly and simply.

1️⃣ <meta charset="utf-8" />

html
<meta charset="utf-8" />

  • Purpose: Tells the browser what character set your page uses.

  • utf-8 is the standard encoding that supports all letters, symbols, and emojis.

  • Without it, some characters (like accents, special symbols, or even some letters) might display incorrectly.

Example problem without it:
If you wrote your bio with “software development – beginner” and the dash doesn’t show correctly, the browser may render weird symbols instead.

✅ Conclusion: It’s best practice to include it.

2️⃣ <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />

html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />

  • Purpose: Makes your page mobile-friendly.

  • Explains to the browser:

    “The page width should match the device screen, and the zoom level starts at 1.”

  • Without this meta tag, your webpage might look tiny on phones and require zooming.

3️⃣ Do you have to include meta?

  • Technically, your page will still load without these <meta> tags.

  • But best practice is to include them, especially if you care about:

    • Correct character display (charset)

    • Mobile responsiveness (viewport)

Bottom line: ✅ Include them. They don’t break anything, and they make your site look correct everywhere.

what is this
ChatGPT said:

Ah! You’re asking about <meta> specifically. Let me explain clearly.

<meta> in HTML

A <meta> tag is an HTML element that provides metadata about your webpage.

  • Metadata = information about your page that isn’t directly shown to the visitor, but tells the browser or search engines how to handle your page.

  • It always goes inside the <head> section of your HTML.

Common <meta> tags

  1. Character encoding

html
<meta charset="utf-8" />

  • Tells the browser which character set to use.

  • utf-8 is standard and supports letters, numbers, symbols, emojis, etc.

  • Without it, some characters might show incorrectly.

  1. Viewport (for mobile devices)

html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />

  • Makes your webpage look good on phones and tablets.

  • Ensures the page scales to the screen size and doesn’t appear zoomed out or tiny.

  1. Other examples (optional)

html
<meta name="description" content="My personal portfolio website">
<meta name="author" content="Blessing Nkosimphile Manhique">

  • These give search engines info about your page and the author.

✅ Do you have to include <meta>?

  • Recommended: Yes, especially charset="utf-8" and the viewport meta.

  • Technically: Your page will work without them, but it might:

    • Show weird characters if you have accents or symbols.

    • Look bad on mobile devices.
